The prophet Elijah prayed for God to send fire down from heaven on Mount Carmel and it came right away (I Kings 18).
The early church prayed for the Apostle Peter to be released from prison and their prayer was answered (Acts 12).
In some cases, God not only answers our prayer, He gives us MORE than we asked.
David’s son from his affair with Bathsheba got sick and David prayed for earnestly for him, fasted and spent nights lying on the ground
Paul had a thorn in the flesh from Satan and he prayed three times for God to remove it and God said, “NO” (II Corinthians 12).
Many times God says NO because what we ask is not good for us or He has something better for us.
Jesus said, “No” but then went and performed a greater miracle by raising him from the dead (John 11).
Later in life, as we look back, we are glad that God did not give us what we prayed for.
Sometimes the answer is not “YES” or “No” but “WAIT”.
God promised him a son in Genesis 12 but he did not get the son God promised him until Genesis 21 and that was twenty-five years later.
According to the early church historian named Eusebius, James “was in the habit of entering the temple alone, and was often found upon his bended knees, and interceding for the forgiveness of the people; so that his knees became hard as camel’s.
As J. Hampton Heathley III notes, “For the size of the epistle, James says more about prayer than any other New Testament book.
In verses 16-17, James gives Elijah as an example of the power we can have in prayer.
He lived in the northern part of Israel in the 9th century B.C. during the reign of King Ahab and Queen Jezebel.
The northern kingdom had nineteen kings and all of them were bad but one of the worst ones was Ahab.
I Kings 16:33 says, “Ahab also made an Asherah pole and did more to provoke the LORD, the God of Israel, to anger than did all the kings of Israel before him.”
Elijah’s Accomplishments 1) He was able to bring fire down from heaven by his prayers.
James doesn’t mention that one but you can read about his great contest with the Baal prophets on Mount Carmel in I Kings 18:16-40.
People prayed to Baal for several hours and they also prayed fervently but not no reply (I Kings 18:26).
Elijah prays a short prayer (only two verses long) but the results were amazing – fire fell from heaven.
2) He was able to have power over sickness and even death by his prayers.
He was able to raise someone from the dead by his prayers (I Kings 17:17-24).
3) He was able to change the weather by his prayers (bring a drought, cause rain to fall).
They didn’t worship in Jerusalem and began worshiping Jehovah through an idol (golden calf at Dan and Bethel).
They didn’t try to start a whole new religion, just to make some changes to it.
The OT predicted drought as a form of judgment on the nation (Deuteronomy 11:16-17).
He was supposed to be the god of rain but he was powerless to give rain, because he did not exist.
How the Prophet Elijah was Different From Us 1) He had a unique authority as a prophet of the Lord.
We do not have that kind of authority, apart from the specific statements of Scripture.
Some would argue he lived in an age of miracles which only happened in certain periods of biblical history (time of Moses and Joshua, time of Elijah and Elisha, time of Jesus and the Apostles).
Instead of talking about the ways we are DIFFERENT from Elijah, James focuses on the ways that we are SIMILAR to Elijah.
In other words, even though he was a great prophet with incredible power, he was also just a man.
How the Prophet Elijah was Just Like Us 1) Elijah had his ups and downs.
2) He lived in a day of moral and spiritual decay, like we live in today.
James says “The prayer of a righteous man is powerful and effective” (5:16).
We don’t have to be a prophet or a miracle worker, we just have to be righteous.
If we pray earnestly like Elijah did, we might get the results that he did.
He was not afraid to pray for big things (raising the dead, calling fire down from heaven).
It is not wrong to pray for little things but we should also pray about big things.
He stretched himself out on the dead widow’s son, not once but three times (I Kings 17:21).
When he prayed for rain, he sent his servant out to check on the answer.
When his servant came back the first time and said, “I see nothing,” Elijah did not give up.
When the servant came back again with nothing to report, Elijah just sent him back out—seven times over (I Kings 18:43).
But if Elijah had quit on the second or third time, or even the fifth or sixth, he might not have seen his answer come forth (cf. Luke 18:1-8).
When the widow’s son died, he carried the boy to his room, laid him on his bed and cried out to God for the boy (I Kings 17:20-22).
When he prayed for rain, he went to the top of Mount Carmel and bent down to the ground and put his face between his knees (I Kings 18:42).
He had so much faith that God would answer his prayer for fire from heaven that he threw in three gallons of water around the altar (I Kings 18:32-33).
As he prayed on Mt. Carmel, he sent his servant to see if his prayer was answered yet.
He expected it to rain after three years of drought after seeing only a tiny cloud form (I Kings 18:44).
He did things in response to God’s command (I Kings 18:36) or prayed based on Scripture (Deuteronomy 11:16-17).
